response.about:
"...This skin. These lips. I look at her and feel overwhelmed by sudden desire to always have this body by my side. When it’s raining. When it’s cold, and I feel so miserable all by myself in a dark room filled with bitter loneliness. When I’m happy, and the world is all on my palms – I’d still need this woman. If touch her once, I’ll stay forever under her spell.
Well, I don’t see her that often – twice a month, maybe. She comes in. Looks around, deep in her daydreams, and gracefully makes her way to international department. Flutters in her airy glam clothing through our standard supermarket, like an exotic butterfly across shaved greenish-brown lawn. The cashiers know I’m after her. Some of them follow her with envious stares, some look at me with sympathy. This kind of girls are not meant for guys like me. But who knows.
She is not an American. Always buys some strange unattractive stuff with titles from some faraway lands. It looks like poison for me.
Does she speak English at all? Does she know what love is? Works for mafia? Prostitute? Hunts for a hub to get a green card? But I look at her, and see her angel’s face, tired eyes and dry rough hands with some cheap manicure – nope, she is not. She cannot be. Just works hard for her American dream to come true.
Standing in a line, she occasionally glances at me with a light smile. Does she know?
Paper or plastic,- I drop in a low voice to the next customer. Plas… — they drop in response, and my hands start packing greasy monster snacks in plastic bags. My hands, but not me. I almost feel her, the silk of her hazel locks on my cheek, her heavenly smooth skin, clean and slightly scented with some foreign aroma. I am flying high!
You know, luv, I will do everything for you. I belong to you. I will never hurt you. I will always love you.
My imaginary kisses cover her and she kisses me back. I am so lucky to have this girl, - at least in my fantasy.
She pays by credit card and leaves."

By Emma Nasipova, 2007
